Hema-Quebec celebrated yesterday on the 10th anniversary of her foundation, and her President, Dr. Francine Décary, had all reason to rejoice because Hema-Quebec has become one of the most secure and efficient blood banks in the world.
And above all, she gained the confidence of the public, which was severely shaken by the scandal of the infected blood in the 1980s and 1990s.
As you know, the national blood reserves managed by the blood donation service of the Canadian Red Cross were contaminated with the HI virus and hepatitis C virus during the 1980s.
In view of this drama and the dissatisfaction of the public, the Canadian Government launched a public investigation conducted by Judge Horace Krever in February 1994, aimed at bringing light into the circumstances which had led to such a tragedy and developing directives to prevent a new disaster of this kind.
While Judge Krever still hesitated to submit his report, several provinces then put a committee on the legs, whose aim was to develop a new system for the management of blood conservation in Canada.
In Quebec, the Gélineau Committee fulfilled this mission.
According to the reports by Gélineau and Krever, two blood banks were founded in Canada: Hema-Quebec, responsible for Quebec, and the Canadian blood company to provide the other provinces and the two territories.
`1998, when Hema-Quebec took up their work, only 38% of the people had confidence in the blood conservation system in Quebec, recalls Dr. Décary.
The situation was discouraging.
By the huge efforts to improve the safety of blood conservations and through the work in this field during the following years, we have won back the public', she says, before proudly stressing that at the beginning of 2008, almost 94% of Quebec's population had confidence in Hema-Quebec.
Dr. Décary, however, maintains in consciousness that 'confidence is something extremely fragile'.
Since its establishment on 28 September 1998, Hema-Quebec has acted in accordance with the principle of caution.
At that time, we experienced the appearance of many cases of the human form of cattle wound in Europe, a new type of Creutzfeldt Jakob disease, this woman, who has been headed since the foundation of 1998.
`And we didn't have the least idea if this disease could be transmitted over the blood.
So we are calling for one of the main directives of the Krever and Gélineau reports, which, according to the use of exclusion measures, if you do not know this, and if a disease is slowly progressing, as it is obviously the case with the Creutzfeldt Jakob disease, which is expressed by a degeneration of the brain, which inevitably leads to death.
Thus, in April 1999, no blood was accepted from people who had stayed in the United Kingdom for more than one month since 1980.
Well, a few years ago, without any doubt, it was proven that this disease is transmitted over the blood.
So this event has shown us that the principle of caution that we applied has quite a sense.
In 1999, a much more precise technique appeared on the market to detect HIV: the nuclear acid tests (NST), which enable the virus itself to prove directly in the blood of the donor, and not that of the antibodies against the virus, as was the case with the tests used before.
The NST made it possible to shorten the incubation time that takes place between the time the person was infected and when the first viruses can be demonstrated in the blood by our techniques, the specialist explains.
This time could be reduced to a duration of less than one week.
Thus, the risk that some donors could be infected without knowing it and you could not recognize this was significantly reduced.
These improvements made it possible to significantly reduce the risk of transmitting AIDS via blood transfusion.
Today, one out of 12 million people is at risk of receiving HIV - infected blood.
`In other words, it means that you have to distribute 12 million blood conservations before someone was caught with HIV.
Since Hema-Quebec distributes between 400,000 and 500,000 blood conservations every year, it would take more than 24 years before a case occurs where HIV was transmitted via a blood conservation.
I think that you can feel well today when you get or write a blood transfusion to restore health, says the head of Chef of Hema-Quebec.
`Our challenge for the next ten years is to maintain the safety of our products.
You don't know what disease viruses can get into the system.
Only last year on the island of Réunion the Chikungunya virus appeared, which, like the West Nile virus, is transmitted by insects over the blood.
We need to monitor without interruption', Dr. Décary continues before she emphasizes that Hema-Quebec also needs to provide an adequate supply in addition to a secure supply.
`The need is growing because the population is ageing.
As treatments for cancer are more aggressive, patients often need new red blood cells or platelets.
The ageing of the population also affects the blood donor network, which averages only 3% of Quebec's inhabitants suitable for blood donation. '
Every healthy person who is 18 years old or older and fulfils suitability criteria can spend blood every 56 days, i.e. six times a year.
By average, 14% of the people who make their blood available are not accepted because they are ill, for example, AIDS or malaria, and those who have travelled to a country where malaria is spread, are excluded from blood donation for one year.
`With these 3% we can get an inventory that meets the needs of hospitals.
Missing stocks are very rare.
But you have to renew the members of this donor network if they get older and donate no more blood.
It is hard to convince people to spend blood, but especially to keep them and to bring them to become regular donors.
Life is so hectic today that you rarely find the time to spend an hour on blood donation', Francine Décary regrets.
With an annual budget of 297 million dollars, Hema-Quebec delivers not only blood conservations, but also human tissues, including bone transplants, heartburns, eyelaps, and skin, which are almost exclusively used for severe burning injuries.
These tissues are examined, processed and frozen before they are stored at Hema-Quebec, which also manages the only public navel blood bank of Quebec.
In the Nabelsnur, which was previously considered biomedical waste, there is a rich blood stem cells that can serve to treat severe diseases, such as leukaemia.
`A few weeks ago, we celebrate the imaging of our thousandth most navel blood sample, and we plan to decrease more than a thousand a year.
