The psychology of excavation - or why we are willing to pay more
In the case of auctions, the buyers are inclined to spend more and therefore to overevaluate the foolbodies.
Neurologists and economic researchers at the University of New York have now managed to discover the neurological and economic foundations of this well-known and seemingly irrational behavior.
According to a study published in the "Science" magazine, people in a competition, such as a sale on eBay, do not want to be slaughtered and are therefore willing to pay even excess prices.
The researchers have tried to explore the neurological scheme of this "game" with experimental auctions.
A group of volunteers should play Lotto while the others participated in a playful action - in both cases the active brain regions of the volunteers were examined using functional magnetic resonance (fMRI).
In both games, the participants were able to win money, but an increased activity of the Striatum, a complex below the brain circus, was measured in the case of losers of the auction, in which the opponent’s survival plays a major role.
In addition to many other functions, this brain region is responsible for the "self reward" of the nervous system.
The researchers therefore believed that the increase in prices could be explained by avoiding an overreaction of the Striatum.
In order to support their these, the economists in the research group have conducted additional studies on the follow-up of the money.
In this case, three groups should offer to one partner under different conditions.
The control group was communicated to the true value of the product, afterwards they made their inputs.
Another group was also promised 15 dollar reward, in the case that they are winners from the game.
The third group received $15 before the auction, which had also been lost in the case of a lost game.
The difference between the two groups was therefore simply that the emphasis was on the one on profit, while the other was on loss.
As evidence of the hypothesis expressed by neurologists, however, the members of the "to lose" group were prepared for higher efforts than those in the control or win group.
"These results cannot be derived from any previous economic theory.
These have just just justified the practices observed in auctions with the joy of gaining or risk prevention.
The contradiction between these two theories has been resolved by the visual neurologic procedures, so that we now have a third explanation" - said Andrew Schotter, Professor of the Economic Faculty of the University of New York.
Hepatitis: When is your doctor inquired?
About half a billion people worldwide suffer from chronic hepatitis B or C, and in Hungary this chronic liver disease is listed among the leading causes of death.
The number of infected persons is estimated to be a hundred thousand, but only seven thousand are treated, which is because the patients often do not know that they are infected.
Hepatitis is the collective term for different virus-infectious liver diseases.
The symptoms are often similar - hepatic inflammation and yellow inflammation are common, but the causes and diseases differ from each other.
Depending on the incidence, the hepatitis virus spreads to two different types: with hepatitis A and E through the digestive traction (for example by contaminated foods or water), hepatitis B, C and D can be transmitted by blood and other body fluids (e.g. sperm, skele secret or spice).
Travellers are recommended to vaccine against the virus A and B at least, there is no vaccine against the virus C.
The symptoms of hepatitis A appear about two-tre weeks after consuming the contaminated food and are generally accompanied by discomfort, weakness, abdominal pain and breakthreat.
Thereafter the yellow liquor appears on the skin and in the eyes, the chair becomes bright, the urine dark, and the recovery can take up to two-three weeks.
Around 1 million people worldwide die of hepatitis B caused, far more severe diseases such as liver cancer and hepatic cirrhosis.
The main reason for this is that, according to estimates, only every tenth infected person is in medical treatment.
Hepatic C may also have serious consequences: untreated may lead to liver cirrhosis and liver cancer.
Most of the infected do not even know about their disease, as the inducer destroys the liver cells stupidly - in many cases the first symptoms appear after 20-30 years.
Therefore, timely prevention, such as regular checks, is essential.
There are three groups in which this disease occurs more frequently: those who have had a blood transfusion before 1991, drug addicts, and tattoo.
Currently, the number of chronic hepatitis C patients is estimated to be 200 million worldwide.
Since the disease is already proven in a routine laboratory study, it is advisable to visit the home doctor in the first signs of unknown origin.
At the right time, the disease is healable, the virus can be eradicated, thus banning the risk of infection and preventing the emergence of cancer.
The 30th September is the World Day of Hepatitis, 2004 for the first time held by patient representatives worldwide.
The objective of the action is to strengthen consciousness for this chronic liver inflammation caused by viruses, their origin and the importance of early identification.
