Intelligent car imitate the flight of the Hummel
What would be the best method for developing new technologies to prevent accidents if not to imitate the obstacle sensors from nature?
For example those of the bees.
The CEATEC in Japan was presented with an amazing project in which the Nissan engineers were inspired of humbling in the creation of new accidents avoiding systems.
In cooperation with the University of Tokyo, Nissan has built the biomimetical system of type BR23C, a mini car equipped with the characteristics of the bees, with the aim of supporting the development of a system that avoids any collisions.
In the flight each bee forms its own oval "Private Area", which is very similar to our own "Shield", said Kazuhhiro Doi, product manager for technology-PR and research development, at the exhibition.
The composite eye of the bee, which can see in every direction and in a angle of more than 300 degrees, plays an important role.
To imitate the function of the composite eye, the researchers took the idea of the laser-controlled distance meter.
This identifies obstacles before the BR23C in a face field of 180 degrees within 2 meters, calculates their distances and sends signals to the microprocessor to board, which immediately initiates the collisions avoiding process.
The obstacle is registered in second break parts, and the authoroboter immediately changes the course, similar to the movement of the bees by turning the tyres around the corresponding angle.
Unlike previous systems, this manoeuvre takes place purely instinctively.
"If not, the authorboter could not respond quickly enough to eliminate the obstacles," explained Toshiyuki Andoh, head of the "Mobility Laboratory" and the authoroboter project.
The system must react instinctively and immediately, as this technology corresponds to the innerest and most vulnerable part of the protective shield - a layer that is currently considered inevitable within the accidents.
The whole process must reflect the behaviour of the bees when they deviate other bees.
And this has to run in the fraction of a second.
However, unlike the bees, the deviation cannot go up, down, or even diagonal - it can only be two-dimensional, only towards the turnability of tyres.
While the bees are infinitely open here to deviate other bees, the researchers were able to use only the rotation movement, the acceleration and brake.
The BR23C contains lithium polymer batteries that are lighter and more energy efficient and therefore have longer life than conventional lithium ion batteries.
Andoh explained that it comes to the instinctive, intelligent response, and less to the processing of the data, and even less to the ability to store it.
This device must process only some inputs per second and respond accordingly to them.
It does not have to save this, or produce an intuitive, logical reaction on the basis of previous manoeuvres, so it is running just using a handful of KB memory.
There is no need for gigabyte and megabyte-wear memories.
This is the first step in the development of immediate collisions prevention technology, which, according to Nissan estimated, will be serial in production within the next ten years.
Another application could find technology in the GPS satellite navigation by consciously directing the driver about obstacles and thus leading it to the goal.
